<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
Illustrations are given here of some of the well-known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1877" class="Arachnida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Bavia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bavia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Bavia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. aericeps" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="aericeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">B. aericeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 36–41" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 36 - 41. Bavia aericeps 36 male left palp, ventral view (specimen 2008 PNG- 2407, Papua New Guinea, 5.231 ° S, 142.532 ° E) 37 same, retrolateral view of tibia 38 female epigyne, ventral (specimen SMF 60114, Samoa) 39 same, vulva. 40, 41 male (specimen 2008 PNG- 1517, Papua New Guinea, 5.283 ° S, 142.498 ° E). Distance between substrate grooves 10 mm. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures36-41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487534" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">36-41</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. sexpunctata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="sexpunctata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">B. sexpunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 54–63" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 54 - 63. Bavia sexpunctata. 54 male left palp, ventral view (Singapore, Upper Peirce Reservoir) 55 same, retrolateral view of tibia 56 epigyne, ventral (Singapore, Bukit Timah) 57 vulva, dorsal 58, 59 male (specimen AS 19.2175, Singapore) 60 - 63 female (specimen AS 19.0230, Singapore). Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures54-63" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487536" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">54-63</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. capistrata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="capistrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">B. capistrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was synonymized without explanation by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Prószyński">Proszynski</normalizedToken>
(2017) with the extremely different 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="C. L. Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Evarcha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Evarcha flavocincta" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavocincta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Evarcha flavocincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, possibly because of superficial similarities in the palp. C. L. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Koch’s">Koch's</normalizedToken>
(1846) illustration of the male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.L.Koch" authorityYear="1846" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Maevia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Maevia capistrata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capistrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Maevia capistrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1877" class="Arachnida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Bavia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bavia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Bavia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by body form and markings. The only doubt about the status of C. L. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Koch’s">Koch's</normalizedToken>
species is which species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1877" class="Arachnida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Bavia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bavia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Bavia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is it precisely. Candidates include the one figured by Cao, Li, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Żabka">Zabka</normalizedToken>
(2016), the one figured here as 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. capistrata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="capistrata">B. cf. capistrata</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 42–53" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 42 - 53. Bavia cf. capistrata. 42 male left palp, ventral view (specimen AS 19.1118, Singapore) 43 same, retrolateral view of tibia 44 epigyne, ventral (specimen AS 19.1128, Singapore) 45 vulva, dorsal 46 - 49 Male AS 19.1118 50 Male AS 19.2341 (Singapore) 51 - 53 female AS 19.1128 (Singapore). Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm; on bodies 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures42-53" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487535" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">42-53</figureCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. nessagyna" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="nessagyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">B. nessagyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 64–75" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 64 - 75. Bavia nessagyna sp. nov. 64 male left palp, ventral view (holotype IDWM. 20005) 65 same, retrolateral view of tibia 66 epigyne, ventral (specimen IDWM. 20003) 67 vulva, dorsal 68, 69 male (specimen SWK 12 - 4726) 70 - 72 male (specimen SWK 12 - 0590) 73 - 75 female (specimen SWK 12 - 4087). Distance between substrate grooves 10 mm. Scale bars: on genitalia 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1004.57526.figures64-75" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/487537" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">64-75</figureCitation>
). The one figured here as 
<taxonomicName family="Salticidae" genus="B." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="B. capistrata" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="capistrata">B. cf. capistrata</taxonomicName>
could be different from that figured by Cao, Li, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Żabka">Zabka</normalizedToken>
. The former shows a slightly wider embolus and more delicate ECP, and possibly more contrasting markings. Regardless, C. L. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Koch’s">Koch's</normalizedToken>
species is removed from synonymy with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="C. L. Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Evarcha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Evarcha flavocincta" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavocincta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Evarcha flavocincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and returned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1877" class="Arachnida" family="Pittosporaceae" genus="Bavia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bavia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Bavia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
